Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} and a knob of @?butter{a knob} in a deep #saucepan{} (with a tight-fitting lid) on medium heat. Once hot, add the onion and fry, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

While the onion softens, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{3} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Once the onion has softened, add the @British smoked bacon lardons{120%g} to the saucepan. Stir-fry, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Cook bacon thoroughly.

Add in the garlic. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir the @basmati rice{150%g} into the onion and lardons until coated, ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @chicken stock paste{15%g}, the @sugar{1%tsp} and @water for the rice{300%ml}. Bring to the boil.

Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the #lid{}.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, quarter the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g}.

When the rice is cooked, add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir through the tomato chunks, @pesto{32%g} and @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g} until well combined.

Taste the rice and season with @?salt{} and @?pepper{} if needed.

Divide the pilaf between your #bowls{}.

Drizzle the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} on top and crumble over the @Greek style salad cheese{50%g} to finish.

Enjoy!